{{Nihongo|'''Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto'''|ツクヨミノミコト, 月読命}},<ref>{{Cite book  |author=平藤喜久子 |editor=[[松村一男]]ほか編 |title=神の文化史事典 |publisher=[[白水社]] |date=February 2013
|isbn=978-4-560-08265-2 |page=285 |chapter=スサノオ 建速須佐之男命（記）、素戔嗚尊（紀） }}</ref> or simply {{Nihongo|'''Tsukuyomi'''|ツクヨミ, 月読}} or {{Nihongo|'''Tsukiyomi'''|ツキヨミ}},<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kotobank.jp/word/キヨミノミコト(月読尊)-99149 |title=ツキヨミノミコト（月読尊） |work=ブリタニカ国際大百科事典 小項目事典 |publisher=[[コトバンク]] |access-date=2016-09-18}}</ref> is the {{ill|List of lunar deities|en|List of lunar deities|WD=Q56351871|lt=moon kami|1=List of lunar deities}} in [[Japanese mythology]] and the [[Shinto]] religion. The name "Tsukuyomi" is a compound of the {{ill|Old Japanese|en|Old Japanese|WD=Q5736700|lt=Old Japanese|1=Old Japanese}} words {{Nihongo||月|tsuku|"moon, month", becoming modern {{ill|Japanese language|en|Japanese language|WD=Q5287|lt=Japanese|1=Japanese language}} ''tsuki''}} and {{Nihongo||読み|yomi|extra="reading, counting"}}.<ref name="KDJ"><span class="book">'''1988''', <cite>''国語大辞典（新装版） ''(Kokugo Dai Jiten, Revised Edition)</cite> (in Japanese), [[w:Tōkyō|Tōkyō]]: [[w:Shogakukan|Shogakukan]]</span></ref>  The ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' mentions this name spelled as {{Nihongo||月弓|Tsukuyumi|extra="moon bow"}}, but this ''yumi'' is likely a variation in pronunciation of ''yomi''.<ref name="KDJ"/> An alternative interpretation is that his name is a combination of {{Nihongo||月夜|tsukiyo|extra="moonlit night"}} and {{nihongo||見|mi|extra="looking, watching"}}. ''-no-Mikoto'' is a common honorific appended to the names of Kami; it may be understood as similar to the English honorific 'the Great'.

There is so little known about Tsukuyomi that even their sex is unknown. Still, in ''{{ill|Man'yōshū|en|Man'yōshū|WD=Q834321|lt=Man'yōshū|1=Man'yōshū}}'', Tsukuyomi's name is sometimes rendered as {{Nihongo|'''Tsukuyomi Otoko'''|月讀壮士|extra="moon-reading man"}}, implying that they are male.<ref><span class="book">c. '''759''': ''{{ill|Man'yōshū|en|Man'yōshū|WD=Q834321|lt=Man'yōshū|1=Man'yōshū}}'', volume 7, poem 1372; in {{ill|Old Japanese|en|Old Japanese|WD=Q5736700|lt=Old Japanese|1=Old Japanese}}.</span>  Text available online [http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man7Yos.html#1372 here].</ref>

Tsukuyomi was the second of the {{Nihongo|"three noble children"|三貴子|Mihashira-no-Uzu-no-Miko}} born when [[Izanagi|Izanagi-no-Mikoto]], the kami who created the first land of [[Onogoro Island|Onogoroshima]], was cleansing himself of his kegare while bathing after escaping the {{ill|Underworld|en|Underworld|WD=Q154365|lt=Underworld|1=Underworld}} and the clutches of his enraged dead sister, {{ill|Izanami|en|Izanami|WD=Q682306|lt=Izanami-no-Mikoto|1=Izanami}}. Tsukuyomi was born when he washed out of Izanagi's right eye.<ref name="Roberts 2010">{{cite book | last = Roberts | first = Jeremy | title = Japanese Mythology A To Z | location  = New York | publisher = Chelsea House Publishers | year = 2010 | edition = 2nd | isbn = 978-1-60413-435-3 | url = http://www.enryo.ro/carti/Japanese%20mythology%20A%20to%20Z.pdf}}</ref> However, in an alternative story, Tsukuyomi was born from a mirror made of white copper in Izanagi's right hand.

Tsukuyomi angered [[Amaterasu]] (who in some sources was his wife) when he killed {{ill|Ukemochi|en|Ukemochi|WD=Q2280323|lt=Ukemochi|1=Ukemochi}}, the megami of food. Amaterasu once sent Tsukuyomi to represent her at a feast presented by Ukemochi. The megami created the food by turning to the ocean and spitting out a fish, then facing a forest and spitting out game, and finally turning to a rice paddy and coughing up a bowl of rice. Tsukuyomi was utterly disgusted by the manner of which the exquisite-looking meal was made in, so he killed her.<ref name="Roberts 2010"/>

Amaterasu learned what happened and she was so angry that she refused to ever look at Tsukuyomi again, forever moving to another part of the sky. This is the reason that day and night are never together. This is according to one of the accounts in the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]''. Tsukuyomi does not have such significance in the ''[[Kojiki]]'', in which there is a similar tale about [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto]] killing a similar food megami named [[:en:Ōgetsuhime|Ōgetsuhime]], who is often conflated with Ukemochi.

